    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, can you help me understand the difference between a \"confidentiality period\" and a \"survival clause\" in a standard contract? I'm trying to make sure I don't miss anything important.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "A confidentiality period and a survival clause are two distinct provisions in a contract, but both serve to protect the interests of one or both parties. A confidentiality period is a clause that restricts the use of confidential information during a specified period after the contract is signed. It's like a temporary shield, shielding sensitive information from prying eyes, just as a group of goblins guarding a treasure hoard would fiercely protect their loot. \n\nOn the other hand, a survival clause is a provision that continues to apply even after a contract is terminated or expires. It's like a time bomb, ticking away, ensuring that certain terms remain in effect even if the rest of the contract is no longer binding. This clause is often used to protect the rights of one party, even if the other party is no longer bound by the contract. \n\nFor example, a survival clause might state that \"the confidentiality provisions shall survive for a period of two years after the contract expires.\" This means that even if the contract is terminated, the confidentiality provisions will remain in effect for two years, giving the parties time to wind down their business relationship. \n\nWhen reviewing a contract, it's essential to pay close attention to both confidentiality periods and survival clauses. You wouldn't want to",
      "source": "target",
